    title: "Prostatitis: NIH Classification & Targeted Therapy",
    cellular: { title: "Pathophysiology of Prostatitis Syndromes", content: "Prostatitis encompasses four distinct syndromes classified by the NIH system based on presence of infection, inflammation, and symptom chronicity. The prostate gland is vulnerable to infection and inflammation due to its anatomical position surrounding the prostatic urethra and its ductal system that allows retrograde ascent of urethral bacteria.\n\nCategory I — Acute Bacterial Prostatitis: Acute infection of the prostate gland, most commonly caused by gram-negative uropathogens (E. coli 80%, Klebsiella, Proteus, Pseudomonas) ascending from the urethra. Presents with acute systemic illness: high fever, chills, dysuria, perineal pain, and obstructive urinary symptoms. The acutely inflamed prostate is boggy, tender, and warm on digital rectal exam (DRE). AVOID vigorous prostate massage — risk of bacteremia. Urine culture is typically positive. Treatment: fluoroquinolones (ciprofloxacin, levofloxacin) or TMP-SMX for 4-6 weeks; IV antibiotics if septic. Acute bacterial prostatitis can progress to prostatic abscess, especially in immunocompromised patients.\n\nCategory II — Chronic Bacterial Prostatitis: Recurrent UTIs caused by the same organism persisting in the prostate despite treatment. Bacteria form biofilms within prostatic ductal system, creating a reservoir for recurrent infection. Symptoms: recurrent UTIs, chronic pelvic pain, dysuria between UTI episodes. Diagnosis: Meares-Stamey 4-glass test or simplified pre/post-massage test showing bacteria in expressed prostatic secretions or post-massage urine. Treatment: fluoroquinolones 6-12 weeks (best prostate penetration) or TMP-SMX.\n\nCategory III — Chronic Prostatitis/Chronic Pelvic Pain Syndrome (CP/CPPS): The MOST COMMON type (~90% of prostatitis cases). Chronic pelvic pain ≥3 months without demonstrable infection. Subdivided into IIIA (inflammatory — WBCs in prostatic secretions) and IIIB (non-inflammatory — no WBCs). Pathophysiology is poorly understood: likely involves neurogenic inflammation, pelvic floor dysfunction, and central sensitization. Treatment is multimodal: alpha-blockers (tamsulosin), anti-inflammatories, pelvic floor physical therapy, psychotherapy for pain management.\n\nCategory IV — Asymptomatic Inflammatory Prostatitis: Incidental finding of WBCs in prostatic tissue or secretions during evaluation for other conditions (infertility, elevated PSA). No treatment required unless associated with infertility." },
